REST APIs (@RestController) return JSON → Next.js fetch(). MVC views (@Controller) render HTML templates
———————-
Implementation: pgvector documents table in Spring Boot, structure models with Entity (DB mapping), DTO (API transfer), and Response (view data) in the model/ folder
———————-
Entity: pgvector column mapping, Hibernate handles SQL
DTO: Clean API contracts, no DB exposure
Response: Frontend-friendly, hides embedding vector
———————————-
Complete Model Structure
———————————-
src/main/java/com/example/docpgvector/model/
├── Document.java              # JPA Entity ← DB table
├── DocumentDto.java           # API input/output
├── DocumentResponse.java      # Controller → frontend
└── DocumentSearchRequest.java # Similarity search
1. Entity (Document.java) - Maps to documents table

package com.example.docpgvector.model;

import jakarta.persistence.*;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.annotation.JsonIgnore;

@Entity
@Table(name = "documents")
public class Document {
    @Id @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;
    
    private String title;
    @Column(columnDefinition = "text")
    private String content;
    
    @Column(name = "embedding", columnDefinition = "vector(1536)")
    @JsonIgnore  // Don't serialize binary vectors
    private float[] embedding;
    
    private LocalDateTime createdAt = LocalDateTime.now();
    
    // constructors, getters, setters
    public Document() {}
}
2. DTOs for API

// DocumentDto.java - For create/update
public record DocumentDto(
    String title, 
    String content, 
    float[] embedding  // From OpenAI API
) {}

// DocumentResponse.java - Clean API response
public record DocumentResponse(
    Long id,
    String title,
    String content,
    LocalDateTime createdAt
) {}
3. Controller Usage

@PostMapping
public DocumentResponse create(@RequestBody DocumentDto dto) {
    Document entity = new Document();
    entity.setTitle(dto.title());
    entity.setContent(dto.content());
    entity.setEmbedding(dto.embedding());
    Document saved = repo.save(entity);
    return new DocumentResponse(saved.getId(), saved.getTitle(), 
                               saved.getContent(), saved.getCreatedAt());
}
